From 90f99944fcdd60bb8d26559ceabc0734691e6b13 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Sat, 2 May 2026 17:16:31 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 092/174] mm/rmap: page_vma_mkclean_one batches via
 pvmw->nr_mmupages
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Mirror the Phase-2b conversion of try_to_unmap_one (commit ff154fa36c21)
and try_to_migrate_one (commit 0452d1cbc36c): batch page_vma_mkclean's
PTE-level work over the kernel page worth of consecutive same-PFN PTEs
the walker yields per yield, instead of operating one PTE at a time.

Before this change the function ran the per-PTE sequence
(flush_cache_page → ptep_clear_flush → wrprotect+mkclean → set_pte_at)
once per yield.  Under PGCL the walker yields PAGE_MMUCOUNT PTEs at a
time, and only the first was processed per yield; the loop then
iterated PAGE_MMUCOUNT times to clean a single kernel page mapping.
Correct results but PAGE_MMUCOUNT× the cache+TLB flushes.

The early-skip (no work needed if no PTE in the batch is dirty or
writable) must scan ALL sub-PTEs.  Sub-page mprotect can leave a
kernel-page mapping with mixed write bits, so checking only the first
PTE could falsely skip a writable sub-PTE and leave it modifiable
during writeback (data corruption).  The peek loop is O(nr_pages) but
typically hits cache.

For the actual cleaning, use:
  flush_cache_range(vma, address, end_addr);
  entry = get_and_clear_ptes(mm, address, pte, nr_pages);
  flush_tlb_range(vma, address, end_addr);
  entry = pte_wrprotect(pte_mkclean(entry));
  set_ptes(mm, address, pte, entry, nr_pages);

get_and_clear_ptes returns the OR'd dirty/accessed bits with the
FIRST PTE's PFN; set_ptes(..., nr_pages) reconstructs the consecutive
sub-page PFNs via pte_advance_pfn, so the per-sub-page PFN topology
is preserved across the round-trip.

For non-PGCL builds nr_mmupages is always 1, the peek loop runs once,
get_and_clear_ptes(..., 1) == ptep_get_and_clear, set_ptes(..., 1) ==
set_pte_at, and behavior is byte-identical to the legacy form.

Verified on x86_64 PGCL=4 (LTP 71p/0f/28s — exact baseline match) and
aarch64 PGCL=4 (cow PASS, PGCL basic 19/19, stress 12/12, all mm
selftests PASS, zero kernel BUG/Oops/WARNING).  Test outcomes byte-
identical to the post-Bug-4-fix baseline.

Signed-off-by: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@gmail.com>
---
 mm/rmap.c | 45 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 41 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/mm/rmap.c b/mm/rmap.c
index 013ca259130e..cae5532a3383 100644
--- a/mm/rmap.c
+++ b/mm/rmap.c
@@ -1148,6 +1148,18 @@ static int page_vma_mkclean_one(struct page_vma_mapped_walk *pvmw)
 		if (pvmw->pte) {
 			pte_t *pte = pvmw->pte;
 			pte_t entry = ptep_get(pte);
+			/*
+			 * Under PGCL the walker yields one kernel page worth
+			 * of consecutive same-PFN PTEs at a time
+			 * (pvmw->nr_mmupages, typically PAGE_MMUCOUNT).  Batch
+			 * the cache+TLB flush, clear, and writeback over the
+			 * whole yielded range; one rmap event per yield.  For
+			 * non-PGCL builds nr_mmupages is always 1 and this
+			 * collapses to the per-PTE legacy form.
+			 */
+			unsigned int nr_pages = pvmw->nr_mmupages, i;
+			unsigned long end_addr;
+			bool any_dirty_or_write = false;
 
 			/*
 			 * PFN swap PTEs, such as device-exclusive ones, that
@@ -1157,14 +1169,39 @@ static int page_vma_mkclean_one(struct page_vma_mapped_walk *pvmw)
 			 */
 			if (!pte_present(entry))
 				continue;
-			if (!pte_dirty(entry) && !pte_write(entry))
+
+			/*
+			 * The early-skip (no work needed if no PTE in the
+			 * batch is dirty or writable) must scan ALL sub-PTEs:
+			 * sub-page mprotect can leave a kernel-page mapping
+			 * with mixed write bits, so checking only the first
+			 * PTE could falsely skip a writable sub-PTE and leave
+			 * it modifiable during writeback (data corruption).
+			 * Loop is O(nr_pages) but typically hits cache.
+			 */
+			for (i = 0; i < nr_pages; i++) {
+				pte_t pe = ptep_get(pte + i);
+
+				if (pte_dirty(pe) || pte_write(pe)) {
+					any_dirty_or_write = true;
+					break;
+				}
+			}
+			if (!any_dirty_or_write)
 				continue;
 
-			flush_cache_page(vma, address, pte_pfn(entry));
-			entry = ptep_clear_flush(vma, address, pte);
+			end_addr = address + nr_pages * MMUPAGE_SIZE;
+			flush_cache_range(vma, address, end_addr);
+			entry = get_and_clear_ptes(vma->vm_mm, address, pte, nr_pages);
+			flush_tlb_range(vma, address, end_addr);
 			entry = pte_wrprotect(entry);
 			entry = pte_mkclean(entry);
-			set_pte_at(vma->vm_mm, address, pte, entry);
+			/*
+			 * set_ptes restores N PTEs with PFN-stride: the OR'd
+			 * pteval keeps the FIRST PTE's PFN; consecutive sub-
+			 * page PFNs are reconstructed by pte_advance_pfn.
+			 */
+			set_ptes(vma->vm_mm, address, pte, entry, nr_pages);
 			ret = 1;
 		} else {
 #ifdef CONFIG_TRANSPARENT_HUGEPAGE
